WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.400
Have you ever seen this diagram? It's from the R for Data Science book, and it describes

00:00:03.400 --> 00:00:06.720
the process that you go through as a data scientist when you approach a new problem.

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:10.120
First, you import your data, and you get it into a nice, tidy format so that the next

00:00:10.120 --> 00:00:14.200
steps are easier. Then you go through a cycle of transforming, visualizing, and modeling

00:00:14.200 --> 00:00:16.959
your data until you have results that you're ready to communicate.

00:00:16.959 --> 00:00:21.240
We often think of this last step of communication as the final step of your project, but in

00:00:21.240 --> 00:00:25.520
reality, this step can happen many times, and Shiny is a great fit for this. Imagine

00:00:25.520 --> 00:00:28.840
that you're working on your project and you realize that you have a choice to make,

00:00:28.840 --> 00:00:32.439
so you throw together a quick Shiny app to show to your colleagues. They give you some

00:00:32.439 --> 00:00:36.320
good feedback, and you go back to the cycle of transforming, visualizing, and modeling

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:40.599
again. You only used that Shiny app once, but it was still useful and helpful in your

00:00:40.599 --> 00:00:44.560
process. In another scenario, you bring a small Shiny app to your colleagues, and they

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:48.520
actually suggest some new features that you could add to the app. And pretty soon you

00:00:48.520 --> 00:00:53.840
have a full-featured web application built from Shiny. And this is why Shiny is great.

00:00:53.840 --> 00:00:57.279
It's perfect for those small apps, and it's robust enough to grow with you to be the final

00:00:57.279 --> 00:00:58.599
product that you deliver.

